For the national level, the higher score (0–1) of the Composite SDG Index for a country in one year implies the better the composite performance of achieving SDGs for that country and the more likely it can achieve SDGs in 2030. Our results showed that all 15 countries have improved their composite performance of achieving SDGs over time (Fig. 8
                        , Table S3), and the change ranged from a 1.83% increase (Turkmenistan) to a 43.67% increase (Estonia) (Table S4). In particular, from 2000 to 2018, among the 15 countries, Russia had the best composite performance of achieving SDGs (from 0.4854 to 0.6422), whereas Uzbekistan and Tajikistan showed the worst composite performance (from 0.2989 to 0.3254, and from 0.3301 to 0.3412, respectively) (Fig. 8, Table S3), and these two countries happened to have the highest urgency to improve the sustainability of the progress of achieving SDGs, even if their progress had been sustainable from 2000 to 2018 (Figs. 4 and 9
                        ).
